"Zocca A., Zanini C., Aimi A., Frigimelica G., La Porta N., Battisti A.","Spread of plant pathogens and insect vectors at the northern range margin of cypress in Italy",2008,"Acta Oecologica","33","3",,"307","313",,,10.1016/j.actao.2008.01.004,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-42749087938&partnerID=40&md5=af25d19b915a55a5baf612a549783ddb","DAAPV, Università di Padova, Via Università, 16a, 35020 Legnaro, PD, Italy; Istituto Agrario di San Michele all'Adige, 38010 San Michele all'Adige, Italy","Zocca, A., DAAPV, Università di Padova, Via Università, 16a, 35020 Legnaro, PD, Italy; Zanini, C., DAAPV, Università di Padova, Via Università, 16a, 35020 Legnaro, PD, Italy, Istituto Agrario di San Michele all'Adige, 38010 San Michele all'Adige, Italy; Aimi, A., DAAPV, Università di Padova, Via Università, 16a, 35020 Legnaro, PD, Italy; Frigimelica, G., DAAPV, Università di Padova, Via Università, 16a, 35020 Legnaro, PD, Italy; La Porta, N., Istituto Agrario di San Michele all'Adige, 38010 San Michele all'Adige, Italy; Battisti, A., DAAPV, Università di Padova, Via Università, 16a, 35020 Legnaro, PD, Italy","The Mediterranean cypress (Cupressus sempervirens) is a multi-purpose tree widely used in the Mediterranean region. An anthropogenic range expansion of cypress has taken place at the northern margin of the range in Italy in recent decades, driven by ornamental planting in spite of climatic constraints imposed by low winter temperature. The expansion has created new habitats for pathogens and pests, which strongly limit tree survival in the historical (core) part of the range. Based on the enemy release hypothesis, we predicted that damage should be lower in the expansion area. By comparing tree and seed cone damage by pathogens and pests in core and expansion areas of Trentino, a district in the southern Alps, we showed that tree damage was significantly higher in the core area. Seed cones of C. sempervirens are intensively colonized by an aggressive and specific pathogen (the canker fungus Seiridium cardinale, Coelomycetes), associated with seed insect vectors Megastigmus wachtli (Hymenoptera Torymidae) and Orsillus maculatus (Heteroptera Lygaeidae). In contrast, we observed lower tree damage in the expansion area, where a non-aggressive fungus (Pestalotiopsis funerea, Coelomycetes) was more frequently associated with the same insect vectors. Our results indicate that both insect species have a great potential to reach the range margin, representing a continuous threat of the arrival of fungal pathogens to trees planted at extreme sites. Global warming may accelerate this process since both insects and fungi profit from increased temperature. In the future, cypress planted at the range margin may then face similar pest and pathogen threats as in the historical range. © 2008 Elsevier Masson SAS. All rights reserved.","Climate change; Cupressus sempervirens; Distribution; Enemy release hypothesis; Seiridium cardinale","comparative study; damage; evergreen tree; fungus; global warming; host-pathogen interaction; human activity; insect; ornamental species; pest species; seed; survival; Eurasia; Europe; Italy; Southern Europe; Trentino-Alto Adige; Trento; Coelomycetes; Cupressus; Cupressus sempervirens; Fungi; Heteroptera; Hexapoda; Hymenoptera; Lygaeidae; Megastigmus wachtli; Orsillus maculatus; Pestalotiopsis funerea; Seiridium cardinale; Torymidae",,,,,,"Agrawal, A.A., Kotanen, P.M., Mitchell, C.E., Power, A.G., Godsoe, W., Klironomos, J., Enemy release? An experiment with congeneric plant pairs and diverse above- and belowground enemies (2005) Ecology, 86, pp. 2979-2989; Ayres, M.P., Lombardero, M.J., Assessing the consequences of climate change for forest herbivore and pathogens (2000) Sci. Total Environ., 262, pp. 263-286; Barthelet, J., Vinot, M., Notes sur les maladies des cultures méridionales (1944) Ann. Epiphyties, 10, pp. 11-23; Battisti, A., Roques, A., Colombari, F., Frigimelica, G., Guido, M., Efficient t